<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1757,2034]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,444,1757,1782]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Comparative discussion.</emphasis>
The freshwater triclad flatworm 
<taxonomicName box="[816,998,1758,1782]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Dugesiidae" genus="Girardia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="tigrina">
<emphasis box="[816,998,1758,1782]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Girardia tigrina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most widespread planarians in North 
<collectingCountry box="[302,398,1794,1818]" name="United States of America" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">America</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kenk" box="[416,553,1794,1818]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Kenk, R. (1944) The freshwater triclads of Michigan. Miscellaneous publications of the Museum of Zoology, 60, 1 - 44." type="journal article" year="1944">
Kenk, 
<number box="[494,553,1794,1818]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1944.0">1944</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Hyman" box="[567,725,1794,1819]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Hyman, L. H. (1951) North American Triclad Turbellaria XII. Synopsis of the known species of freshwater planaria of North America. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 70, 154 - 167." type="journal article" year="1951">
Hyman, 
<number box="[666,725,1794,1818]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1951.0">1951</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mettrick" box="[738,970,1794,1818]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Mettrick, D. F., Boddington, M. J. &amp; Gelder, S. R. (1970) Distribution of freshwater triclads (Platyhelminthes: Turbellaria) in Central Southern Ontario. In: Proceedings 13 th Conference on Great Lakes Research, 71 - 81." type="proceedings paper" year="1970">
Mettrick 
<emphasis box="[844,902,1794,1818]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[911,970,1794,1818]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1970.0">1970</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler" box="[984,1323,1794,1818]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Chandler, C. M. &amp; Darlington, J. T. (1986) Further field studies on freshwater planarians of Tennessee (Turbellaria: Tricladida): Western Tennessee. Journal of Freshwater Ecology, 3, 493 - 501." type="journal article" year="1986">
Chandler &amp; Darlington, 
<number box="[1264,1323,1794,1818]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1986.0">1986</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Thorp" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Thorp, J. H. &amp; Covich, A. P., Eds. (1991) Ecology and classification of North American freshwater invertebrates. Academic Press, San Diego." type="book" year="1991">
Thorp &amp; Covich, 
<number box="[247,304,1830,1854]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1991.0">1991</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and has successfully invaded several European countries (
<bibRefCitation author="Dahm" box="[982,1127,1830,1854]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Dahm, A. G. (1955) Dugesia tigrina (Girard) an American immigrant into European waters. Proceedings International Association Theoretical and Applied Limnology, 12, 554 - 561." type="journal article" year="1955">
Dahm, 
<number box="[1068,1127,1830,1854]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1955.0">1955</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gourbault" box="[1140,1329,1830,1854]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Gourbault, N. (1969) Expansion de Dugesia tigrina (Girard), planaire Americaine introduite en Europe. Annales de Limnologies, 5, 3 - 7." type="journal article" year="1969">
Gourbault, 
<number box="[1270,1329,1830,1854]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1969.0">1969</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Van" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Van Der Velde, G. (1975) The immigrant triclad flatworm Dugesia tigrina (Girard) (Plathelminthes, Turbellaria). Range-extension and ecological position in The Netherlands. Aquatic Ecology, 9, 123 - 130." type="journal article" year="1975">
Van Der Velde, 
<number box="[231,290,1866,1890]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1975.0">1975</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ball" box="[304,601,1866,1890]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Ball, I. R. &amp; Reynoldson, T. B. (1981) British planarians. Cambridge University Press, Synopses of the British fauna (new series), 19, 141 pp." type="book" year="1981">
Ball &amp; Reynoldson, 
<number box="[542,601,1866,1890]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ribas" box="[615,815,1866,1890]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Ribas, M., Riutort, M. &amp; Baguna, J. (1989) Morphological and biochemical variation in populations of Dugesia (G.) tigrina (Turbellaria, Tricladida, Paludicola) from the western Mediterranean: biogeographical and taxonomical implications. Journal of Zoology (London), 218, 609 - 626." type="journal article" year="1989">
Ribas 
<emphasis box="[688,747,1866,1890]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[756,815,1866,1890]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gee" box="[829,1062,1866,1891]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Gee, H. &amp; Young, J. O. (1993) The food niches of the invasive Dugesia tigrina (Girard) and indigenous Polycelis tenuis Ijima and Polycelis nigra (Muller) (Turbellaria: Tricladida) in a Welsh Lake. Hydrobiologia, 254, 99 - 106." type="journal article" year="1993">
Gee &amp; Young, 
<number box="[1005,1062,1866,1890]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1993.0">1993</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) as well as 
<collectingCountry box="[1203,1270,1867,1890]" name="Japan" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Japan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1283,1386,1866,1890]" name="Australia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Australia</collectingCountry>
and South 
<collectingCountry box="[222,318,1902,1926]" name="United States of America" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">America</collectingCountry>
(Sluys 
<emphasis box="[403,459,1902,1926]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[464,524,1902,1926]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1995.0">1995</number>
). This eurythermic species (
<bibRefCitation author="Claussen" box="[836,1128,1902,1926]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Claussen, D. L. &amp; Walters, L. M. (1982) Thermal acclimation in the fresh water planarians, Dugesia tigrina and D. dorotocephala. Hydrobiologia, 94, 231 - 236." type="journal article" year="1982">
Claussen &amp; Walters, 
<number box="[1071,1128,1902,1926]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) has been reported in many areas in the eastern sector of the Iberian Peninsula and the Balearic Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Baguna" box="[1008,1225,1938,1962]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Baguna, J., Salo, E. &amp; Romero, R. (1980) Les planaries d'aigues dolces a Catalunya i les illes Balears. 1. Clau sistematica i distribucio geografica. Butlleti de la Institucio Catalana d'Historia Natural, 45, 15 - 30." type="journal article" year="1980">
Baguñà 
<emphasis box="[1103,1159,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
1980
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Baguna" box="[1237,1296,1938,1962]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Baguna, J., Salo, E. &amp; Romero, R. (1981) Biogeografia de las planarias de aguas dulces (Platelminthes; Turbellaria; Tricladida; Paludicola) en Espana. Datos preliminares. Actas del Primer Congreso de la Sociedad Espanola de Limnologia, 265 - 280." type="book chapter" year="1981">1981</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ribas" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Ribas, M., Riutort, M. &amp; Baguna, J. (1989) Morphological and biochemical variation in populations of Dugesia (G.) tigrina (Turbellaria, Tricladida, Paludicola) from the western Mediterranean: biogeographical and taxonomical implications. Journal of Zoology (London), 218, 609 - 626." type="journal article" year="1989">
Ribas 
<emphasis box="[1380,1436,1938,1962]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[151,208,1974,1998]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) and on one occasion in Galicia in northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[757,821,1974,1998]" name="Spain" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Spain</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[836,909,1974,1998]" name="Serbia" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Servia</collectingCountry>
<emphasis box="[917,974,1974,1998]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[981,1042,1974,1998]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="2006.0">2006</number>
). It has also been reported in some isolated areas of central 
<collectingCountry box="[423,487,2010,2034]" name="Spain" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Spain</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Baguna" box="[501,718,2010,2034]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Baguna, J., Salo, E. &amp; Romero, R. (1981) Biogeografia de las planarias de aguas dulces (Platelminthes; Turbellaria; Tricladida; Paludicola) en Espana. Datos preliminares. Actas del Primer Congreso de la Sociedad Espanola de Limnologia, 265 - 280." type="book chapter" year="1981">
Baguñà 
<emphasis box="[596,652,2010,2034]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[659,718,2010,2034]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gamo" box="[729,1021,2010,2034]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Gamo, J. &amp; Gourbault, N. (1981) Presence du Turbellarie nearctique Dugesia tigrina (Girard) en Espagne. Bulletin du Musem National d'Histoire Naturelle, Paris 4 e ser. 3, 147 - 150." type="book chapter" year="1981">
Gamo &amp; Gourbault, 
<number box="[961,1021,2010,2034]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,151,319]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Sampling at many localities of the Mediterranean area of the Iberian Peninsula have yielded specimens with external traits that correspond to one of the two known asexual strains of 
<emphasis box="[975,1078,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">G. t i g r i n a</emphasis>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ribas" box="[1134,1330,188,212]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refString="Ribas, M., Riutort, M. &amp; Baguna, J. (1989) Morphological and biochemical variation in populations of Dugesia (G.) tigrina (Turbellaria, Tricladida, Paludicola) from the western Mediterranean: biogeographical and taxonomical implications. Journal of Zoology (London), 218, 609 - 626." type="journal article" year="1989">
Ribas 
<emphasis box="[1206,1262,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[1269,1330,188,212]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
): a markedly triangular head; two large and close-set eyes anterior to prominent auricular slits; a blotchy and grey dorsal surface; a pale ventral surface. However, the species is very scarce in Galicia and in the Cantabrian coastal region (records for the latter region are new; 
<figureCitation box="[576,644,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1930,1953]" captionTargetBox="[153,1430,1016,1892]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,1016,1893]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distributional records of Girardia tigrina in the Iberian Peninsula. Data from Baguñà et al. 1980, 81; Ribas, 1990; Altaba et al. 1991; Servia et al. 2006; unpublished records, this study." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206800/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<number box="[628,644,295,319]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). All of the animals that were collected were asexual.
</paragraph>
